1
00:02:22,580 --> 00:02:24,100
<i>NARRATOR: Once upon a time,</i>

2
00:02:24,220 --> 00:02:26,260
<i>there was a brave little mouse</i>

3
00:02:26,340 --> 00:02:29,860
<i>who loved honor and justice
and always told the truth.</i>

4
00:02:30,500 --> 00:02:31,740
(CAPTAIN BARKING ORDERS)

5
00:02:43,860 --> 00:02:45,500
<i>No, that's not him.</i>

6
00:02:45,700 --> 00:02:46,660
(YAWNING)

7
00:02:47,140 --> 00:02:48,580
<i>That's a rat.</i>

8
00:02:48,900 --> 00:02:49,980
<i>And anyone who knows anything,</i>

9
00:02:50,020 --> 00:02:52,500
<i>knows there's a big difference
between a mouse and a rat.</i>

10
00:02:52,580 --> 00:02:53,540
Ohhh.

11
00:02:53,820 --> 00:02:56,220
<i>First of all, rats hate the light.</i>

12
00:02:57,380 --> 00:02:58,460
(GROANS)

13
00:02:59,060 --> 00:03:01,540
<i>They spend their lives in the darkness.</i>

14
00:03:01,860 --> 00:03:03,100
<i>They're also terrified of people,</i>

15
00:03:03,140 --> 00:03:05,180
<i>which is why they slink
and cower all the time.</i>

16
00:03:05,300 --> 00:03:06,300
Ooh!

17
00:03:06,620 --> 00:03:08,700
<i>And as far as telling the truth is concerned,</i>

18
00:03:08,820 --> 00:03:11,460
<i>well, that's impossible
because, as everyone knows,</i>

19
00:03:11,740 --> 00:03:12,740
(CLEARS THROAT)

20
00:03:12,860 --> 00:03:14,500
<i>a rat can't talk.</i>

21
00:03:14,660 --> 00:03:16,100
Tell me that thing again, please.

22
00:03:16,580 --> 00:03:17,700
Come on.

23
00:03:18,340 --> 00:03:19,580
Just once, I promise.

24
00:03:19,700 --> 00:03:20,740
Tell me one more time,

25
00:03:20,860 --> 00:03:22,460
and I won't ask you ever again. I swear.

26
00:03:22,500 --> 00:03:23,580
(SIGHS)

27
00:03:23,620 --> 00:03:26,460
Fine. We are headed to Dor,

28
00:03:26,500 --> 00:03:29,180
one of the most
magical places in the whole world.

29
00:03:29,300 --> 00:03:30,780
No, that's not what you said before.

30
00:03:30,820 --> 00:03:33,300
You know, every place
has something special.

31
00:03:33,380 --> 00:03:35,740
And, in Dor, it's the soup!

32
00:03:35,860 --> 00:03:37,500
SAILOR: Land ho!

33
00:03:37,620 --> 00:03:39,420
(SAILORS CHEER)

34
00:03:41,540 --> 00:03:42,500
Ohhh.

35
00:03:43,620 --> 00:03:44,980
SAILOR 1: It's down below, I tell you.

36
00:03:45,060 --> 00:03:46,020
SAILOR 2: Give it a heave.

37
00:03:50,940 --> 00:03:52,340
I can see it!

38
00:03:54,660 --> 00:03:58,260
Ooh, I can smell it! I can smell it.

39
00:04:05,300 --> 00:04:07,740
ROSCURO: Oh, I can't wait
to taste the soup!

40
00:04:08,020 --> 00:04:09,460
Just stay close.

41
00:04:09,540 --> 00:04:10,740
We leave again at 6:00.

42
00:04:10,820 --> 00:04:13,540
You know, we ought to think
about staying here just a little longer.

43
00:04:13,620 --> 00:04:15,540
Don't even think about it.

44
00:04:15,780 --> 00:04:16,820
Remember Shanghai?

45
00:04:16,900 --> 00:04:18,420
Yeah, but this place is different.

46
00:04:18,820 --> 00:04:20,700
I mean, this is special.

47
00:04:23,140 --> 00:04:26,660
<i>NARRATOR: On any given day,
just one whiff from one of the soup shops</i>

48
00:04:26,780 --> 00:04:29,060
<i>was almost like having a full meal.</i>

49
00:04:29,700 --> 00:04:32,540
<i>But on one very special day every year,</i>

50
00:04:32,580 --> 00:04:35,460
<i>the kingdom of Dor
was magically transformed.</i>

51
00:04:35,540 --> 00:04:37,940
(CROWD CHEERING)

52
00:04:38,020 --> 00:04:39,900
<i>In Dor, Christmas was nothing.</i>

53
00:04:40,020 --> 00:04:41,500
<i>Well, they still celebrated it,</i>

54
00:04:41,620 --> 00:04:44,220
<i>but it was nothing compared to Soup Day.</i>

55
00:04:49,060 --> 00:04:50,020
Watch it, watch it.

56
00:04:50,140 --> 00:04:51,940
Incoming potatoes!

57
00:04:52,020 --> 00:04:53,660
Hurry! Hurry! Excuse us.

58
00:04:53,780 --> 00:04:56,700
<i>Every Dorian, young and old,
would flock toward the castle</i>

59
00:04:56,820 --> 00:04:59,740
<i>because they knew that, at that very moment,</i>

60
00:04:59,780 --> 00:05:02,300
<i>deep within the royal kitchens,</i>

61
00:05:02,420 --> 00:05:04,220
<i>a masterpiece was being created.</i>

62
00:05:04,260 --> 00:05:05,980
DELIVERY MAN: Potatoes coming up!

63
00:05:13,060 --> 00:05:14,100
COOK 1: Let's go!

64
00:05:14,180 --> 00:05:15,140
COOK 2: Don't forget the parsley!

65
00:05:15,460 --> 00:05:16,860
COOK 1: Make sure it's clean!

66
00:05:27,460 --> 00:05:29,500
<i>NARRATOR: Everyone knew
Chef Andre was a genius,</i>

67
00:05:29,620 --> 00:05:33,820
<i>but they got reminded of it
on the first Sunday of every spring.</i>

68
00:05:35,580 --> 00:05:37,820
<i>At exactly 12:00 noon,</i>

69
00:05:37,860 --> 00:05:41,180
<i>he would unveil that year's royal creation.</i>

70
00:05:53,660 --> 00:05:54,740
More onions!

71
00:05:54,820 --> 00:05:55,780
More onions!

72
00:05:55,900 --> 00:05:56,860
More onions!

73
00:05:56,980 --> 00:05:57,980
More onions!

74
00:05:59,580 --> 00:06:01,460
<i>They would jam the town square,</i>

75
00:06:01,540 --> 00:06:03,740
<i>and, as the aroma began to build,</i>

76
00:06:03,780 --> 00:06:05,820
<i>so did their anticipation.</i>

77
00:06:08,380 --> 00:06:10,180
- Ohhh!
- Ow!

78
00:06:10,300 --> 00:06:11,260
Sorry.

79
00:06:11,380 --> 00:06:13,020
(TRUMPET FANFARE PLAYING)

80
00:06:13,060 --> 00:06:14,100
(CROWD CHEERING)

81
00:06:19,380 --> 00:06:20,380
Wow.

82
00:06:23,060 --> 00:06:24,060
Thank you.

83
00:06:24,180 --> 00:06:25,180
(CLEARS THROAT)

84
00:06:25,380 --> 00:06:30,020
It's my pleasure to announce
this year's royal creations

85
00:06:30,260 --> 00:06:32,460
from the kitchens of Chef Andre.

86
00:06:32,940 --> 00:06:34,140
Oh, no, no, no, no, no!

87
00:06:34,260 --> 00:06:35,660
Something is wrong.

88
00:06:35,740 --> 00:06:37,300
I need more time!

89
00:06:37,420 --> 00:06:38,620
But we're late already!

90
00:06:38,700 --> 00:06:40,220
This is not right!

91
00:06:42,300 --> 00:06:43,740
Everyone out!

92
00:06:44,140 --> 00:06:45,140
Out!

93
00:06:48,500 --> 00:06:51,980
<i>NARRATOR: Now, it's hard to
be a genius all by yourself.</i>

94
00:06:52,500 --> 00:06:56,140
<i>In fact, sometimes, it takes a little help.</i>

95
00:07:18,580 --> 00:07:19,940
You changed something.

96
00:07:20,260 --> 00:07:22,260
You're crazy. I did not touch it.

97
00:07:22,340 --> 00:07:23,380
- I can smell it.
- Hmm?

98
00:07:23,460 --> 00:07:24,500
- What's this?
- What?

99
00:07:24,580 --> 00:07:26,140
- This!
- Ow! Garlic.

100
00:07:26,540 --> 00:07:27,660
- Garlic.
- Yeah, a little garlic.

101
00:07:28,260 --> 00:07:29,740
- It was already there.
- No.

102
00:07:29,820 --> 00:07:30,780
- Yes.
- No.

103
00:07:30,900 --> 00:07:31,900
- Yes.
- Not this much!

104
00:07:32,020 --> 00:07:33,020
Ow!

105
00:07:33,100 --> 00:07:34,140
You ruined my soup!

106
00:07:34,260 --> 00:07:35,620
I save your soup!

107
00:07:35,700 --> 00:07:40,500
Those people wait all year,
and you want to give them this dishwater.

108
00:07:41,220 --> 00:07:42,460
Dishwater?

109
00:07:42,540 --> 00:07:43,740
Dishwater.

110
00:07:43,820 --> 00:07:44,860
Dishwater?

111
00:07:44,940 --> 00:07:45,980
Ow! Cut it out!

112
00:07:46,140 --> 00:07:47,340
(CLAMORING)

113
00:07:48,700 --> 00:07:49,940
(CROWD CHEERING)

114
00:07:50,020 --> 00:07:51,700
And this year's soup is

115
00:07:53,660 --> 00:07:55,540
a spring tureen

116
00:07:55,620 --> 00:07:57,260
<i>with a mélange of roasted vegetables...</i>

117
00:07:57,340 --> 00:07:58,300
Oh.

118
00:07:58,420 --> 00:08:00,060
...fresh herbs...
- Mmm!

119
00:08:00,180 --> 00:08:01,780
...and wild mushrooms.

120
00:08:01,860 --> 00:08:02,940
Oh.

121
00:08:03,580 --> 00:08:04,780
Roscuro?

122
00:08:08,780 --> 00:08:10,180
Roscuro?

123
00:08:10,780 --> 00:08:12,460
Oh. Evening.

124
00:08:16,300 --> 00:08:20,580
CHEF ANDRE: I don't have to stand here
and listen to a big talking garbage can!

125
00:08:20,740 --> 00:08:24,220
BOLDO: Ha! And I don't have
to stand here and listen to a coward!

126
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:25,980
- Coward?
- Yes, a coward!

127
00:08:26,100 --> 00:08:27,860
- You call me coward?
- Yes!

128
00:08:27,940 --> 00:08:29,620
(SCREAMS)

129
00:08:30,180 --> 00:08:31,380
(GASPS)

130
00:08:31,780 --> 00:08:33,180
Oh, no!

131
00:08:40,740 --> 00:08:41,740
(EXCLAIMS)

132
00:08:44,140 --> 00:08:45,660
(BOLDO YELPS)

133
00:08:49,980 --> 00:08:51,420
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.

134
00:08:51,500 --> 00:08:53,020
(MUTTERING) That did it.

135
00:08:57,220 --> 00:08:58,900
- Hmm?
- Mmm.

136
00:08:59,300 --> 00:09:00,540
BOTH: Mmm!

137
00:09:00,900 --> 00:09:02,420
(CHUCKLES)

138
00:09:02,500 --> 00:09:04,620
<i>- Bellissima!
- It's fantastique!</i>

139
00:09:04,700 --> 00:09:07,540
Roscuro! Roscuro, where are you?

140
00:09:08,660 --> 00:09:10,140
(TRUMPET FANFARE PLAYING)

141
00:09:10,660 --> 00:09:11,740
Ohhh.

142
00:09:18,780 --> 00:09:19,980
(DRUM ROLLS)

143
00:09:23,540 --> 00:09:24,820
(ALL GASP)

144
00:09:30,180 --> 00:09:31,220
(SNIFFS)

145
00:09:31,300 --> 00:09:32,460
Whoa!

146
00:09:47,620 --> 00:09:48,700
(SNIFFS)

147
00:09:53,260 --> 00:09:54,380
<i>Voilà!</i>

148
00:09:54,660 --> 00:09:57,580
This is amazing!

149
00:09:57,820 --> 00:09:59,420
CHEF ANDRE: Wait till
Your Highness tastes it.

150
00:10:01,620 --> 00:10:02,620
Hmm?

151
00:10:13,980 --> 00:10:15,260
QUEEN: This is...

152
00:10:15,380 --> 00:10:16,380
Whoa!

153
00:10:16,460 --> 00:10:18,380
...absolutely...

154
00:10:18,460 --> 00:10:19,420
(EXCLAIMS)

155
00:10:19,540 --> 00:10:23,220
Oh, it moved! My soup moved!

156
00:10:23,380 --> 00:10:25,500
No, it isn't... It did not move.

157
00:10:26,140 --> 00:10:27,260
Oh, Your Highness.

158
00:10:27,380 --> 00:10:28,380
- Ahhh!
- Darling?

159
00:10:28,500 --> 00:10:31,380
Oh! A rat! There's a rat in my soup!

160
00:10:31,460 --> 00:10:33,020
Madam, I know that this is unfortunate.

161
00:10:33,100 --> 00:10:35,180
And I know that
while on first glance, I might...

162
00:10:35,260 --> 00:10:37,300
- A rat! In my soup!
- No. Please. Shh, shh, shh.

163
00:10:37,380 --> 00:10:39,380
- And I ate it!
- Your Highness, hold on...

164
00:10:39,460 --> 00:10:40,460
(GAGGING)

165
00:10:40,540 --> 00:10:42,260
- Uh-oh.
- She's right! It's a rat!

166
00:10:42,340 --> 00:10:43,380
(GASPS)

167
00:10:43,460 --> 00:10:45,420
- Please...
- Ahhh! It's a rat!

168
00:10:46,260 --> 00:10:49,180
Get me that rat!

169
00:10:49,500 --> 00:10:51,100
Now, I really believe
you're jumping to conclusions.

170
00:10:51,620 --> 00:10:53,020
And I'm sure that the rats you met last time

171
00:10:53,140 --> 00:10:55,260
might have caused you
to create a stereotype,

172
00:10:55,340 --> 00:10:56,860
but... But I... But...

173
00:10:56,940 --> 00:10:59,100
It's just... I'm just...
I'm not really from around here.

174
00:10:59,180 --> 00:11:00,860
I'm... I'm from... Oh...

175
00:11:00,940 --> 00:11:01,980
Oh!

176
00:11:02,060 --> 00:11:03,460
That's very aggressive.

177
00:11:03,980 --> 00:11:05,020
GUARD: Get him!

178
00:11:05,100 --> 00:11:06,140
Kitchen...

179
00:11:06,220 --> 00:11:07,420
He's going into the kitchen!

180
00:11:09,700 --> 00:11:10,700
Oh!

181
00:11:15,420 --> 00:11:16,420
GUARD: Over there!

182
00:11:17,580 --> 00:11:19,140
Stop that rat!

183
00:11:19,900 --> 00:11:21,060
Whoa!

184
00:11:21,820 --> 00:11:22,820
GUARD: I got him!

185
00:11:22,900 --> 00:11:23,940
Uh-oh.

186
00:11:30,580 --> 00:11:33,140
He's going near the soup!

187
00:11:36,340 --> 00:11:37,340
GUARD: There he is!

188
00:11:37,500 --> 00:11:39,380
lf... If I could just tell...

189
00:11:39,820 --> 00:11:42,620
GUARD: On the kettle!
That's him, right there!

190
00:11:46,820 --> 00:11:47,820
Look, up there!

191
00:11:55,260 --> 00:11:56,260
(SIGHS)

192
00:11:57,660 --> 00:11:59,420
Sweetie? Darling?

193
00:12:00,780 --> 00:12:02,260
She's... She's...

194
00:12:03,700 --> 00:12:06,220
She's...

195
00:12:06,900 --> 00:12:09,460
Blimey, she's dead. Get him!

196
00:12:09,540 --> 00:12:11,220
GUARD: Don't let him escape!

197
00:12:11,300 --> 00:12:13,460
We'll get you, you rowdy rat!

198
00:12:14,980 --> 00:12:16,100
Oh!

199
00:12:19,940 --> 00:12:20,940
No, no, no!

200
00:12:21,020 --> 00:12:22,660
No, not there!

201
00:13:11,180 --> 00:13:13,140
(SOBBING)

202
00:13:21,820 --> 00:13:23,860
You don't need to be afraid.

203
00:13:25,020 --> 00:13:27,860
I know it's dark, but you'll get used to it.

204
00:13:28,540 --> 00:13:30,260
Who... Who are you?

205
00:13:31,020 --> 00:13:33,220
Just a rat, like you.

206
00:13:34,820 --> 00:13:36,220
Come with me.

207
00:13:48,140 --> 00:13:51,820
<i>NARRATOR: When something
hurts this much, there must be a reason.</i>

208
00:13:52,660 --> 00:13:54,860
<i>There must be someone to blame.</i>

209
00:13:58,540 --> 00:13:59,700
(CLEARS THROAT)

210
00:14:01,060 --> 00:14:04,100
"From this moment on, soup,

211
00:14:04,180 --> 00:14:09,500
"the making of soup,
the selling of soup, or the eating of soup,

212
00:14:09,740 --> 00:14:12,780
"is hereby outlawed in the kingdom of Dor!

213
00:14:20,460 --> 00:14:23,700
"Rats are to be considered illegal as well

214
00:14:23,780 --> 00:14:28,260
"and are hereby deemed
unlawful creatures in the kingdom of Dor!

215
00:14:28,340 --> 00:14:29,580
"From this moment on,

216
00:14:29,660 --> 00:14:34,700
"anyone harboring, sheltering
or possessing a rat in any way,

217
00:14:34,780 --> 00:14:37,220
"shall face the full wrath of the law!"

218
00:14:38,500 --> 00:14:40,260
<i>NARRATOR: So think about this.</i>

219
00:14:40,340 --> 00:14:44,940
<i>What happens when you make something
illegal that is just a natural part of the world?</i>

220
00:14:46,660 --> 00:14:48,660
<i>You may as well make flies illegal.</i>

221
00:14:48,740 --> 00:14:50,860
<i>Or sweat. Or Monday morning.</i>

222
00:14:51,740 --> 00:14:55,060
<i>But that's what the King did
out of a terrible sadness.</i>

223
00:14:59,100 --> 00:15:01,580
<i>Sunlight left and the world went gray.</i>

224
00:15:02,860 --> 00:15:06,740
<i>Colors faded into each other and
dark clouds filled the sky.</i>

225
00:15:08,740 --> 00:15:12,700
<i>And for a long time, it wouldn't rain.</i>

226
00:15:16,220 --> 00:15:21,940
<i>The clouds just stayed
and stayed and stayed.</i>

227
00:15:28,140 --> 00:15:29,820
(SIGHS)

228
00:15:31,820 --> 00:15:33,580
I wish it would rain.

229
00:15:34,300 --> 00:15:35,700
You and the whole world, madam.

230
00:15:36,660 --> 00:15:37,660
Ow!

231
00:15:37,740 --> 00:15:38,820
Oh, sorry, milady!

232
00:15:39,460 --> 00:15:41,900
Well, at least I can still feel that.

233
00:15:44,820 --> 00:15:48,700
Louise, do you think there's a bit of light

234
00:15:49,340 --> 00:15:50,420
somewhere in the world?

235
00:15:50,940 --> 00:15:51,980
Don't know, ma'am.

236
00:15:52,060 --> 00:15:53,620
I think there is.

237
00:15:54,500 --> 00:15:57,060
You just need to know where to find it.

238
00:16:08,740 --> 00:16:11,020
<i>NARRATOR: Okay, remember
when we told you how,</i>

239
00:16:11,140 --> 00:16:13,860
<i>once upon a time,
there was this brave little mouse?</i>

240
00:16:13,940 --> 00:16:17,340
<i>Well, if you know anything about fairytales,</i>

241
00:16:17,420 --> 00:16:21,460
<i>you know that a hero doesn't appear</i>

242
00:16:21,540 --> 00:16:23,740
<i>until the world really needs one.</i>

243
00:16:33,140 --> 00:16:34,700
(MICE SCREAMING)

244
00:16:37,140 --> 00:16:38,220
MOUSE: Oh, look out!

245
00:16:38,340 --> 00:16:41,380
Alms for the blind! Alms for the blind!

246
00:16:42,100 --> 00:16:43,100
(EXCLAIMS)

247
00:16:47,300 --> 00:16:48,340
(MICE CHATTERING)

248
00:17:18,020 --> 00:17:19,220
Excuse me. Excuse me.

249
00:17:19,780 --> 00:17:21,060
Excuse me.

250
00:17:21,540 --> 00:17:22,820
Excuse me.

251
00:17:23,540 --> 00:17:24,900
- Whoa!
- I'm sorry. Sorry.

252
00:17:24,980 --> 00:17:26,140
- Tilling?
- Oh!

253
00:17:26,500 --> 00:17:28,140
Mr. Mayor, hello!

254
00:17:28,260 --> 00:17:29,340
Where are you going?

255
00:17:29,420 --> 00:17:33,100
(STAMMERS) Oh, well, my baby is having a...

256
00:17:33,220 --> 00:17:36,180
No, my wife is having a...

257
00:17:36,300 --> 00:17:38,300
Oh, right. Congratulations.

258
00:17:38,580 --> 00:17:39,860
Thank you. Thank you, sir.

259
00:17:40,420 --> 00:17:42,660
I'm sorry, I... I really... Goodbye.

260
00:17:51,300 --> 00:17:52,900
His eyes are open.

261
00:17:52,980 --> 00:17:54,340
Don't worry about it.

262
00:17:54,380 --> 00:17:56,020
Sometimes they are.

263
00:17:56,100 --> 00:17:57,580
But he isn't cowering.

264
00:17:57,700 --> 00:17:59,420
He's looking right at us.

265
00:17:59,500 --> 00:18:01,860
Don't worry. He'll learn to cower.

266
00:18:02,260 --> 00:18:03,940
They all do in time.

267
00:18:04,820 --> 00:18:06,260
ANTOINETTE: But he isn't!

268
00:18:12,820 --> 00:18:16,940
Wow! He's so puny! And look at those ears!

269
00:18:17,900 --> 00:18:19,300
<i>NARRATOR: And, from the very beginning,</i>

270
00:18:19,380 --> 00:18:21,500
<i>Despereaux Tilling heard more,</i>

271
00:18:21,580 --> 00:18:25,220
<i>saw more and even smelled more
than any of the other mice.</i>

272
00:18:30,820 --> 00:18:32,660
Despereaux, don't do it.

273
00:18:41,140 --> 00:18:42,140
(GASP)

274
00:18:43,460 --> 00:18:44,580
MOUSE 1: Don't look. Don't look!

275
00:18:44,660 --> 00:18:45,700
MOUSE 2: I won't, I won't.

276
00:18:46,820 --> 00:18:47,820
(GROANS)

277
00:18:53,540 --> 00:18:54,540
Mmm.

278
00:18:55,140 --> 00:18:57,900
<i>NARRATOR: Despereaux Tilling
had no idea he was small.</i>

279
00:18:58,980 --> 00:19:01,380
<i>He wasn't just small in human terms.</i>

280
00:19:01,540 --> 00:19:03,940
<i>He was small even for a mouse.</i>

281
00:19:04,620 --> 00:19:07,580
<i>But, to tell you the truth,
he didn't even notice.</i>

282
00:19:07,860 --> 00:19:11,980
<i>In fact, in his own mind,
Despereaux was a giant.</i>

283
00:19:21,420 --> 00:19:23,140
We're worried about him.

284
00:19:23,220 --> 00:19:25,220
He doesn't scurry. He doesn't cower.

285
00:19:25,300 --> 00:19:27,460
At first, we thought he would
grow out of it, but...

286
00:19:27,540 --> 00:19:29,380
Well, he scurries sometimes.

287
00:19:29,460 --> 00:19:30,740
But not when he's scared!

288
00:19:30,820 --> 00:19:31,820
He just does it for fun.

289
00:19:31,940 --> 00:19:33,380
And he never cowers.

290
00:19:33,460 --> 00:19:34,540
We've showed him how, but he...

291
00:19:34,660 --> 00:19:37,020
Well, some kids are slower than others.

292
00:19:37,100 --> 00:19:39,140
He'll cower in time. We'll work on it.

293
00:19:39,220 --> 00:19:41,660
- Yes, but...
- It'll be fine, I promise.

294
00:19:42,340 --> 00:19:44,180
All right, settle down.

295
00:19:44,740 --> 00:19:46,180
Ready, class?

296
00:19:50,060 --> 00:19:51,060
(ALL GASP)

297
00:19:51,820 --> 00:19:52,900
Good.

298
00:19:55,140 --> 00:19:56,580
ALL: Mmm! Ah!

299
00:19:57,620 --> 00:19:59,140
Good. Excellent.

300
00:20:01,700 --> 00:20:03,740
(ALL SCREAM)

301
00:20:09,220 --> 00:20:11,460
- Despereaux!
- Yes?

302
00:20:11,540 --> 00:20:12,580
You didn't cower.

303
00:20:13,220 --> 00:20:14,180
Looks like a sword.

304
00:20:14,260 --> 00:20:16,660
It's a carving knife.

305
00:20:17,700 --> 00:20:19,820
It's beautiful!

306
00:20:19,940 --> 00:20:21,340
It's dangerous.

307
00:20:21,700 --> 00:20:23,580
Do you have anymore?

308
00:20:27,300 --> 00:20:29,220
Despereaux, what are you doing?

309
00:20:29,300 --> 00:20:30,740
We're not even supposed to be here.

310
00:20:30,820 --> 00:20:32,340
That's the dungeon.

311
00:20:32,420 --> 00:20:33,780
They have rats down there.

312
00:20:33,860 --> 00:20:35,300
And they'll eat you.

313
00:20:35,380 --> 00:20:37,220
And pull your arms off!

314
00:20:40,420 --> 00:20:42,020
How far down is it?

315
00:20:43,140 --> 00:20:45,380
I don't know. No one's ever come back.

316
00:20:45,460 --> 00:20:46,660
How come?

317
00:20:46,740 --> 00:20:48,140
'Cause... 'Cause...

318
00:20:48,300 --> 00:20:49,900
'Cause that's where you go when you get...

319
00:20:50,020 --> 00:20:51,380
(STAMMERING) When you get...

320
00:20:51,460 --> 00:20:52,620
Banished.

321
00:20:53,580 --> 00:20:54,860
What do you get banished for?

322
00:20:55,140 --> 00:20:56,380
Oh, you know.

323
00:20:56,460 --> 00:20:57,660
- Rules and...
- Breaking.

324
00:20:57,780 --> 00:20:58,980
- We can't even...
- Talk about it...

325
00:20:59,060 --> 00:21:00,100
- Because...
- That's one of the...

326
00:21:00,740 --> 00:21:01,780
ALL: Rules!

327
00:21:04,420 --> 00:21:05,740
MOUSE 1: Despereaux!

328
00:21:07,300 --> 00:21:09,620
I just want to have a quick look.

329
00:21:09,860 --> 00:21:11,580
We got to get out of here!

330
00:21:13,580 --> 00:21:14,740
MOUSE 1: Oh, gosh.
MOUSE 2: Oh, no.

331
00:21:14,820 --> 00:21:15,900
ALL: Oh, jeez.

332
00:21:15,980 --> 00:21:17,100
Uh-oh.

333
00:21:31,300 --> 00:21:33,460
Despereaux! You can't feed them.

334
00:21:36,940 --> 00:21:38,340
Hello?

335
00:21:38,900 --> 00:21:42,300
(ECHOES)

336
00:21:44,140 --> 00:21:46,780
Here you go, whoever you are.

337
00:21:55,940 --> 00:21:57,020
(CHUCKLING) Nice.

338
00:22:29,620 --> 00:22:30,820
You are crazy!

339
00:22:30,900 --> 00:22:32,300
What I say? I said nothing!

340
00:22:32,420 --> 00:22:33,740
Well, you heard exactly what I said.

341
00:22:33,860 --> 00:22:35,340
- I say you crazy.
- No, no, no, no!

342
00:22:39,820 --> 00:22:41,500
(PLAYING MUSIC)

343
00:22:46,820 --> 00:22:48,460
(ALARM BELL RINGING)

344
00:22:50,980 --> 00:22:52,220
RAT: Hurry!

345
00:22:54,500 --> 00:22:56,020
(RATS CHANTING)

346
00:23:03,060 --> 00:23:05,180
(CROWD CHEERS)

347
00:23:05,260 --> 00:23:07,140
SMUDGE: Ha! They look hungry, sir.

348
00:23:07,180 --> 00:23:08,380
Mmm-hmm.

349
00:23:11,020 --> 00:23:12,340
Dinnertime.

350
00:23:14,180 --> 00:23:16,100
(CLAMORING)

351
00:23:18,980 --> 00:23:20,020
(CHUCKLES)

352
00:23:28,740 --> 00:23:30,300
You're not eating.

353
00:23:30,380 --> 00:23:32,660
Uh, I was.

354
00:23:32,740 --> 00:23:34,980
No, you weren't.

355
00:23:35,060 --> 00:23:38,340
Well, I'm just watching, sir.

356
00:23:38,820 --> 00:23:42,260
Well, that's not very grateful of you

357
00:23:42,340 --> 00:23:45,340
after I've taken you under my wing.

358
00:23:45,700 --> 00:23:49,860
(STAMMERING) Well, I'm grateful, really.
I am.

359
00:23:50,100 --> 00:23:51,940
You miss something, don't you?

360
00:23:52,020 --> 00:23:53,860
Uh, no, I don't.

361
00:23:54,020 --> 00:23:56,300
There's nothing up there, Roscuro.

362
00:23:56,900 --> 00:23:58,140
Nothing at all.

363
00:23:58,220 --> 00:24:00,580
Oh, no, I know that! Absolutely.

364
00:24:00,900 --> 00:24:03,420
Uh, nothing!

365
00:24:04,020 --> 00:24:05,940
Nothing. Nothing at all.

366
00:24:06,140 --> 00:24:07,540
He's a tough one.

367
00:24:07,660 --> 00:24:10,260
You're not gonna turn him. Nah, you're not.

368
00:24:10,340 --> 00:24:14,700
Oh, I don't know. A rat is a rat.

369
00:24:15,180 --> 00:24:18,300
It doesn't really matter where you come from.

370
00:24:46,900 --> 00:24:48,180
ROSCURO: I'm sorry.

371
00:24:59,740 --> 00:25:01,140
MOUSE: He is so weird.

372
00:25:01,340 --> 00:25:02,380
(LAUGHS) No kidding.

373
00:25:03,100 --> 00:25:04,980
That is so beautiful.

374
00:25:05,060 --> 00:25:06,340
I wonder what's out there.

375
00:25:24,420 --> 00:25:26,580
"February 1: Doesn't scurry.

376
00:25:26,660 --> 00:25:28,580
"February 3: Didn't cower.

377
00:25:28,660 --> 00:25:30,380
"Didn't cower. Didn't cower.

378
00:25:30,460 --> 00:25:31,860
"Wouldn't scurry."

379
00:25:31,940 --> 00:25:35,300
Oh, here's one:
"Drew pictures of cats on his notebook."

380
00:25:35,380 --> 00:25:37,300
- No! Cats?
- Oh! I can't imagine!

381
00:25:37,660 --> 00:25:40,700
I'm afraid so. Named it Fluffy.

382
00:25:41,300 --> 00:25:44,820
- Oh, I had no idea!
- Oh! That's terrible.

383
00:25:46,940 --> 00:25:48,660
- Despereaux.
- Yes, sir?

384
00:25:48,940 --> 00:25:50,180
Come in, please.

385
00:25:54,020 --> 00:25:55,940
Despereaux, why do you think
you're in school?

386
00:25:57,300 --> 00:25:58,380
To learn?

387
00:25:58,460 --> 00:25:59,500
- To learn, yes.
- Yes.

388
00:25:59,580 --> 00:26:00,580
To learn what?

389
00:26:01,700 --> 00:26:06,340
(HESITATING) To learn
how to be a mouse, sir.

390
00:26:06,780 --> 00:26:08,180
That is correct.

391
00:26:08,300 --> 00:26:10,620
And you can't be a mouse if
you don't learn to be afraid.

392
00:26:11,420 --> 00:26:13,060
Oh, Despereaux, this...

393
00:26:13,140 --> 00:26:15,980
There's so many
wonderful things in life to be afraid of

394
00:26:16,060 --> 00:26:17,860
if you'd just learn how scary they are.

395
00:26:18,020 --> 00:26:20,100
Yes. Yes, sir.

396
00:26:23,860 --> 00:26:25,060
How about his brother?

397
00:26:25,140 --> 00:26:26,420
His brother? What about him?

398
00:26:26,500 --> 00:26:29,340
Yes, is he, you know, timid?

399
00:26:29,940 --> 00:26:31,940
Oh! Oh, yes!

400
00:26:32,100 --> 00:26:33,700
- Yes, very timid.
- Yes. So timid!

401
00:26:33,780 --> 00:26:35,420
As timid as the day is long.

402
00:26:35,540 --> 00:26:36,820
Good. Good.

403
00:26:37,020 --> 00:26:39,580
Sometimes they just need
to see the older ones do it.

404
00:26:39,660 --> 00:26:41,140
No one starts out afraid.

405
00:26:41,500 --> 00:26:43,260
- Understood.
- Of course.

406
00:26:43,980 --> 00:26:45,460
- You coddle that boy, that's the problem.
- No.

407
00:26:45,540 --> 00:26:46,540
- Yes, you do.
- No, no.

408
00:26:46,620 --> 00:26:48,540
- Yes, you do. You've been doing it for years.
- He was always...

409
00:26:48,660 --> 00:26:49,660
He's little. I've had to help him.

410
00:26:49,740 --> 00:26:52,300
He's not going to be afraid unless
you allow him to be afraid.

411
00:26:52,380 --> 00:26:53,660
Well, Furlough will teach him.

412
00:26:59,700 --> 00:27:00,660
Do what he does.

413
00:27:00,780 --> 00:27:01,940
And don't do anything he doesn't.

414
00:27:02,020 --> 00:27:03,340
And if he's afraid of something...

415
00:27:03,420 --> 00:27:05,020
Then you need to be afraid of it, too.

416
00:27:25,100 --> 00:27:26,140
Oh!

417
00:27:30,780 --> 00:27:31,820
Wow.

418
00:27:44,860 --> 00:27:46,940
Come on, Furlough, hurry up!

419
00:27:50,780 --> 00:27:51,820
Whoa...

420
00:28:02,700 --> 00:28:05,460
FURLOUGH: All right, now, you start
nibbling right along that edge there.

421
00:28:06,260 --> 00:28:09,500
The glue is all right,
but it's the pages that taste the best.

422
00:28:10,140 --> 00:28:13,940
Hmm. "Once upon a time."
That's great, isn't it?

423
00:28:14,340 --> 00:28:15,740
"Upon a time."

424
00:28:15,940 --> 00:28:17,780
And they don't even tell you
what time that is yet.

425
00:28:17,860 --> 00:28:19,580
It's like you have to find that out.

426
00:28:19,700 --> 00:28:22,580
You're not supposed to read it, Despereaux.
You're supposed to eat it.

427
00:28:23,900 --> 00:28:26,100
Good. I'll come back in an hour.

428
00:28:27,220 --> 00:28:31,420
And no reading! It's a rule.

429
00:28:44,540 --> 00:28:48,140
<i>NARRATOR: Once upon a time,
there lived a fair princess,</i>

430
00:28:49,100 --> 00:28:51,420
<i>fairer than any in any other land.</i>

431
00:28:52,660 --> 00:28:54,260
Hmm. Fair.

432
00:28:55,060 --> 00:28:59,820
<i>And, as the story goes,
she was locked up in a faraway castle,</i>

433
00:28:59,940 --> 00:29:03,220
<i>where she could see the world
but could never touch it.</i>

434
00:29:05,980 --> 00:29:07,860
<i>She longed for a prince.</i>

435
00:29:08,660 --> 00:29:11,620
<i>A brave knight who would
deliver her from all of this.</i>

436
00:29:11,740 --> 00:29:15,460
<i>Someone with courage
and honor and decency.</i>

437
00:29:21,220 --> 00:29:23,260
<i>But in a cruel and frightened world,</i>

438
00:29:23,380 --> 00:29:25,340
<i>men like this were scarce indeed.</i>

439
00:29:26,180 --> 00:29:27,220
(DRAGON ROARING)

440
00:29:28,700 --> 00:29:29,660
(GRUNTS)

441
00:30:05,540 --> 00:30:07,660
<i>They lived in a special world</i>

442
00:30:08,140 --> 00:30:11,460
<i>built on courage and chivalry and honor.</i>

443
00:30:11,740 --> 00:30:13,820
<i>They pledged their lives to each other.</i>

444
00:30:14,220 --> 00:30:17,380
<i>To fight for truth, to defend the weak,</i>

445
00:30:17,500 --> 00:30:21,060
<i>to seek justice, and to always...</i>

446
00:30:25,540 --> 00:30:26,860
LESTER: How was the library?

447
00:30:26,980 --> 00:30:27,980
Fine.

448
00:30:28,540 --> 00:30:30,180
Spoil your appetite?

449
00:30:30,500 --> 00:30:32,700
No. Helped it, actually.

450
00:30:33,260 --> 00:30:34,820
Made me hungrier.

451
00:30:36,300 --> 00:30:37,500
Good lad.

452
00:30:40,460 --> 00:30:41,820
Ha-hah!

453
00:30:44,140 --> 00:30:47,500
Did you see they're putting up
a new front on the crumb shop?

454
00:30:47,620 --> 00:30:50,140
ANTOINETTE: Oh! But I loved the old front.
LESTER: Quite modern. Yes.

455
00:30:56,700 --> 00:30:58,780
<i>NARRATOR: Did a book ever speak to you?</i>

456
00:30:59,140 --> 00:31:01,500
<i>Almost like it was written for you?</i>

457
00:31:02,180 --> 00:31:04,060
<i>Despereaux loved it all.</i>

458
00:31:04,420 --> 00:31:05,980
<i>Every bit of it.</i>

459
00:31:06,140 --> 00:31:09,340
<i>The truth, the justice, the bravery,</i>

460
00:31:09,700 --> 00:31:11,340
<i>the sword-fighting.</i>

461
00:31:13,340 --> 00:31:16,060
<i>He even loved things you wouldn't suspect.</i>

462
00:31:17,060 --> 00:31:19,260
<i>The story said she was a prisoner,</i>

463
00:31:19,340 --> 00:31:21,420
<i>but that wasn't totally true</i>

464
00:31:21,540 --> 00:31:25,340
<i>because she had hope,
and whenever you have hope,</i>

465
00:31:25,380 --> 00:31:27,460
<i>you're never really anybody's prisoner.</i>

466
00:31:28,100 --> 00:31:30,140
Someday, my prince will come.

467
00:31:30,700 --> 00:31:32,700
<i>But how did she know that?</i>

468
00:31:32,900 --> 00:31:34,940
Yeah, how did she know that?

469
00:31:36,940 --> 00:31:38,860
(LUTE PLAYING)

470
00:31:48,620 --> 00:31:49,660
(SNIFFLES)

471
00:32:01,700 --> 00:32:02,700
(GASPS)

472
00:32:15,020 --> 00:32:16,220
(PRINCESS PEA CRYING)

473
00:32:21,220 --> 00:32:22,660
DESPEREAUX: Why are you crying?

474
00:32:22,700 --> 00:32:23,700
(GASPS)

475
00:32:24,940 --> 00:32:26,660
Why are you crying?

476
00:32:28,100 --> 00:32:29,660
Down here.

477
00:32:29,940 --> 00:32:31,220
(GASPS) Are you a rat?

478
00:32:31,620 --> 00:32:32,580
No.

479
00:32:32,660 --> 00:32:34,260
What are you? A mouse?

480
00:32:37,100 --> 00:32:38,500
I am a gentleman.

481
00:32:39,460 --> 00:32:40,420
(CHUCKLES)

482
00:32:41,380 --> 00:32:42,820
And how do you do?

483
00:32:45,220 --> 00:32:46,180
You're sad.

484
00:32:46,980 --> 00:32:48,020
Yes.

485
00:32:48,300 --> 00:32:49,340
Because you have longing.

486
00:32:51,500 --> 00:32:52,940
You're a strange little mouse.

487
00:32:53,700 --> 00:32:54,700
Thank you.

488
00:32:58,260 --> 00:32:59,460
Come on.

489
00:33:07,220 --> 00:33:08,540
Where did you hear that?

490
00:33:09,420 --> 00:33:10,940
About the longing.

491
00:33:11,020 --> 00:33:12,300
In a story.

492
00:33:12,420 --> 00:33:14,340
A story? About what?

493
00:33:14,820 --> 00:33:17,420
About a princess, like you,
in a castle, like this.

494
00:33:18,500 --> 00:33:21,300
Oh. You're a smooth little mouse, aren't you?

495
00:33:22,500 --> 00:33:24,900
Bet you tell that to all the princesses.

496
00:33:25,260 --> 00:33:27,020
I am sworn to tell the truth.

497
00:33:27,300 --> 00:33:28,660
It is a code of honor.

498
00:33:28,740 --> 00:33:33,300
Ah. Not just a gentleman,
an honorable gentleman.

499
00:33:34,700 --> 00:33:37,300
Well, then, how does this story end

500
00:33:37,380 --> 00:33:39,460
with this princess who's locked in a castle?

501
00:33:39,540 --> 00:33:40,900
I don't know...

502
00:33:41,220 --> 00:33:42,660
I haven't finished it yet.

503
00:33:43,700 --> 00:33:45,020
I'd love to know.

504
00:33:46,020 --> 00:33:47,940
Oh, I wish it would rain.

505
00:33:48,340 --> 00:33:50,380
I wish there was soup again.

506
00:33:50,540 --> 00:33:52,580
I even wish there were rats!

507
00:33:53,700 --> 00:33:55,380
Will you promise me that?

508
00:33:55,460 --> 00:33:57,900
Will you promise to finish your story
and tell me how it ends?

509
00:33:58,420 --> 00:34:00,780
Yes. It will be my quest.

510
00:34:01,740 --> 00:34:04,980
Your quest! You are a very brave mouse.

511
00:34:11,140 --> 00:34:13,180
Thank you, my good gentleman.

512
00:34:19,220 --> 00:34:20,220
Whoa!

513
00:34:22,740 --> 00:34:23,820
Whoa.

514
00:34:28,660 --> 00:34:29,660
(EXCLAIMS)

515
00:34:32,940 --> 00:34:33,940
Whoa!

516
00:34:36,500 --> 00:34:37,540
(EXCLAIMS)

517
00:34:47,220 --> 00:34:50,420
<i>NARRATOR: Now, there are
all kinds of princesses.</i>

518
00:34:52,100 --> 00:34:53,940
<i>Some are born that way,</i>

519
00:34:54,020 --> 00:34:55,660
<i>some marry into it,</i>

520
00:34:55,860 --> 00:34:59,340
<i>and some are destined to be princesses</i>

521
00:34:59,420 --> 00:35:00,780
<i>only in their own minds.</i>

522
00:35:02,420 --> 00:35:04,020
<i>But at one time or another,</i>

523
00:35:04,100 --> 00:35:07,020
<i>every little girl longs to be a princess.</i>

524
00:35:09,220 --> 00:35:10,820
I'm gonna live right there.

525
00:35:10,940 --> 00:35:13,740
Right up there, near the tippy-top.

526
00:35:14,980 --> 00:35:18,180
Quit your daydreaming and feed those swine!

527
00:35:18,860 --> 00:35:21,340
Yes, I know. It's gonna be all mine.

528
00:35:22,060 --> 00:35:26,780
No, you deaf little urchin.
I said feed those swine!

529
00:35:26,860 --> 00:35:27,860
(EARS RINGING)

530
00:35:30,340 --> 00:35:32,340
<i>NARRATOR: Miggery Sow had been
shoveling slop</i>

531
00:35:32,420 --> 00:35:34,420
<i>for as long as she could remember.</i>

532
00:35:34,620 --> 00:35:38,260
<i>Her Uncle Ned had put a shovel in her hand
from the minute she could hold one.</i>

533
00:35:39,020 --> 00:35:40,980
<i>But it turned out all right</i>

534
00:35:41,060 --> 00:35:42,980
<i>because she got on
quite nicely with the pigs.</i>

535
00:35:43,060 --> 00:35:44,460
That's right.

536
00:35:44,740 --> 00:35:48,500
I'm gonna have a special room
just for my dresses

537
00:35:48,740 --> 00:35:52,220
and another whole closet
just for my knickers!

538
00:35:52,340 --> 00:35:56,060
<i>In fact, Miggery Sow could
see her future so clearly.</i>

539
00:35:56,620 --> 00:36:00,620
<i>She could see the tiara, the fancy dresses,
the maids-in-waiting,</i>

540
00:36:01,260 --> 00:36:04,140
<i>and when things got
really bad around the farm,</i>

541
00:36:04,220 --> 00:36:08,420
<i>she could see the moment that she would
finally be delivered from all of this.</i>

542
00:36:08,860 --> 00:36:10,180
Not long now.

543
00:36:10,260 --> 00:36:11,900
I promise you that.

544
00:36:12,300 --> 00:36:16,780
20 for the big ones,
15 for the sow, and 12 for the girl.

545
00:36:17,220 --> 00:36:19,700
15 for the girl, same as the sow.

546
00:36:21,100 --> 00:36:24,580
I told you! I told you I'd make it to the castle!

547
00:36:24,700 --> 00:36:26,100
Whoa!

548
00:36:27,700 --> 00:36:30,780
<i>So sometimes, it doesn't take much
for your dreams to come true.</i>

549
00:36:31,700 --> 00:36:34,460
<i>You just have to be able to see it that way.</i>

550
00:36:35,220 --> 00:36:38,580
She was beautiful! Like an angel.

551
00:36:39,060 --> 00:36:40,660
FURLOUGH: You are crazy.

552
00:36:40,820 --> 00:36:43,380
And she smelled so amazing.

553
00:36:43,940 --> 00:36:45,060
Like a garden.

554
00:36:45,540 --> 00:36:46,540
Despereaux!

555
00:36:46,620 --> 00:36:48,500
You can't talk to a human.

556
00:36:48,620 --> 00:36:50,020
That is the worst thing you can do.

557
00:36:50,100 --> 00:36:51,940
No, it's the best thing I ever did.

558
00:36:52,100 --> 00:36:53,420
They will throw you in the dungeon.

559
00:36:53,500 --> 00:36:54,980
You will get eaten by rats!

560
00:36:55,060 --> 00:36:56,260
It would be worth it.

561
00:36:56,700 --> 00:36:58,580
They could tear at my flesh.

562
00:36:58,660 --> 00:36:59,980
Oh, this is bad.

563
00:37:00,060 --> 00:37:02,380
Oh, and when she held me
in her hand, it was...

564
00:37:02,940 --> 00:37:06,140
It was so soft, like floating in a pillow.

565
00:37:06,500 --> 00:37:07,860
You know what? I'm worried about you.

566
00:37:08,180 --> 00:37:09,780
That's the point, Furlough.

567
00:37:09,860 --> 00:37:11,580
There's nothing to be afraid of.

568
00:37:11,660 --> 00:37:13,580
Quiet! They will hear you.

569
00:37:13,660 --> 00:37:15,340
Come on. Just try it.

570
00:37:15,620 --> 00:37:18,220
Just for a second, just try being brave.

571
00:37:18,380 --> 00:37:20,140
- Oh!
- And stop cowering!

572
00:37:20,260 --> 00:37:22,420
What's going on in here?

573
00:37:22,500 --> 00:37:26,940
What's all this talk
about princesses and bravery?

574
00:37:27,940 --> 00:37:30,460
Furlough, I want to see you
in my study, right now.

575
00:37:33,860 --> 00:37:35,980
LESTER: Are you sure?
FURLOUGH: That's what he said.

576
00:37:36,060 --> 00:37:38,380
- A real human?
- A princess.

577
00:37:38,460 --> 00:37:39,420
(SIGHS)

578
00:37:39,980 --> 00:37:41,020
We need to tell them.

579
00:37:41,140 --> 00:37:42,620
We need to tell the Mouse Council.

580
00:37:42,740 --> 00:37:44,940
- But they'II...
- This is bad. This is very bad.

581
00:37:45,020 --> 00:37:47,860
If they find out...
If they find out that they didn't find out...

582
00:37:47,980 --> 00:37:50,900
Oh, then they'll find out that it was me who...

583
00:37:50,980 --> 00:37:52,020
Oh, no.

584
00:37:52,100 --> 00:37:54,140
But they will send him to the dungeon!

585
00:37:54,540 --> 00:37:57,020
- Oh, he'll get eaten by rats!
- Oh!

586
00:37:57,100 --> 00:37:58,540
No, not if we beg.

587
00:37:58,620 --> 00:38:02,460
If we really beg
and show them that he's changed.

588
00:38:02,860 --> 00:38:04,140
That he's afraid.

589
00:38:04,220 --> 00:38:07,540
That he's afraid,
and he's turned into a real mouse.

590
00:38:08,300 --> 00:38:09,620
Despereaux!

591
00:38:18,820 --> 00:38:21,260
<i>NARRATOR: Of course,
destiny is a funny thing.</i>

592
00:38:21,860 --> 00:38:25,340
<i>We go out to meet it,
and we don't always know that we are.</i>

593
00:38:34,500 --> 00:38:35,980
KNIGHT: For glory and honor!

594
00:38:36,100 --> 00:38:37,500
Surround him!

595
00:38:54,300 --> 00:38:55,540
MAYOR: Despereaux Tilling.

596
00:38:55,620 --> 00:38:56,620
(GASPS)

597
00:38:58,540 --> 00:39:01,300
How long have you been
working on this book?

598
00:39:01,380 --> 00:39:03,260
Hmm... A week?

599
00:39:03,380 --> 00:39:05,500
A week? You've hardly cracked it.

600
00:39:06,340 --> 00:39:07,740
Well, I was...

601
00:39:09,060 --> 00:39:10,780
I just wanted to see how it ends.

602
00:39:11,660 --> 00:39:13,820
(BELL TOLLS)

603
00:39:16,060 --> 00:39:17,260
(CROWD MURMURING)

604
00:39:21,060 --> 00:39:23,060
INQUISITOR: Refused training as a mouse.

605
00:39:23,140 --> 00:39:26,420
Refused to respect the will
and guidance of elder mice.

606
00:39:26,860 --> 00:39:30,380
Repeatedly engaged in bold
and un-meek behavior.

607
00:39:30,500 --> 00:39:35,260
Triggered willfully
not less than 17 mousetraps.

608
00:39:35,420 --> 00:39:36,380
(CROWD GASPS)

609
00:39:36,500 --> 00:39:37,500
Just shameful!

610
00:39:37,620 --> 00:39:39,740
Had personal contact with...

611
00:39:40,420 --> 00:39:41,380
With...

612
00:39:44,260 --> 00:39:45,340
With a human being.

613
00:39:45,460 --> 00:39:47,140
(CROWD MURMURING)

614
00:39:47,300 --> 00:39:49,340
Isn't there something you can do?

615
00:39:49,380 --> 00:39:51,380
Antoinette, stop right now! Stop that.

616
00:39:51,460 --> 00:39:52,860
You have to trust them.

617
00:39:52,900 --> 00:39:54,420
They are the Council.

618
00:39:54,500 --> 00:39:56,580
They're the Council because...

619
00:39:56,860 --> 00:39:59,260
Because they're the Council.

620
00:40:00,860 --> 00:40:02,260
They're the Council.

621
00:40:02,900 --> 00:40:04,540
Is there anything you wish to say
in your defense?

622
00:40:05,540 --> 00:40:09,140
Well, it was a very good story,

623
00:40:09,980 --> 00:40:13,300
and she was a very beautiful princess.

624
00:40:13,860 --> 00:40:15,260
(CROWD MURMURING)

625
00:40:15,940 --> 00:40:17,820
Despereaux Tilling,

626
00:40:17,860 --> 00:40:21,340
our laws are here
to protect us and our way of life.

627
00:40:21,940 --> 00:40:25,300
And when one of our citizens
strays from that way of life,

628
00:40:25,700 --> 00:40:27,860
he becomes a threat to us all.

629
00:40:28,420 --> 00:40:30,260
It's an easy question.

630
00:40:31,140 --> 00:40:33,380
Are you a man or are you a mouse?

631
00:40:36,340 --> 00:40:37,620
And your actions have told us

632
00:40:37,700 --> 00:40:40,580
that you have a great deal
of trouble being a mouse.

633
00:40:41,980 --> 00:40:43,740
It is the judgment of this court

634
00:40:43,860 --> 00:40:46,300
that you should be banished
from these walls forever.

635
00:40:46,980 --> 00:40:50,620
You shall be remanded
into the custody of Hovis, the Threadmaster,

636
00:40:50,660 --> 00:40:53,820
who will prepare you
for your descent into the dungeons of Dor,

637
00:40:53,860 --> 00:40:57,340
from which no mouse
and no light has ever escaped.

638
00:41:08,900 --> 00:41:10,980
- Shh!
- My baby!

639
00:41:11,140 --> 00:41:14,580
Quiet. Be quiet, my dear.
There's nothing to be done.

640
00:41:39,060 --> 00:41:40,420
Come with me.

641
00:41:48,540 --> 00:41:49,820
Stand there.

642
00:42:00,740 --> 00:42:01,740
Red?

643
00:42:02,020 --> 00:42:03,900
Ah, so they tell me.

644
00:42:06,180 --> 00:42:08,060
So you're the brave one.

645
00:42:09,100 --> 00:42:10,180
I guess.

646
00:42:10,300 --> 00:42:12,700
It's good. It'll carry well down there.

647
00:42:14,340 --> 00:42:15,900
Wear it proudly.

648
00:42:16,740 --> 00:42:18,180
There's no shame.

649
00:42:20,900 --> 00:42:22,140
It's time.

650
00:42:24,900 --> 00:42:28,060
It's all right.
They're too scared to come down here.

651
00:42:34,220 --> 00:42:35,420
In there?

652
00:42:35,780 --> 00:42:37,220
I'm afraid so.

653
00:42:38,980 --> 00:42:40,460
Courage, right?

654
00:42:40,580 --> 00:42:41,820
And truth.

655
00:42:42,380 --> 00:42:44,260
- And honor.
- Good.

656
00:42:44,380 --> 00:42:46,820
But especially courage.

657
00:42:58,180 --> 00:42:59,140
I'm ready.

658
00:42:59,260 --> 00:43:01,180
All right, then you need to...

659
00:43:04,100 --> 00:43:05,180
(EXCLAIMS)

660
00:43:17,220 --> 00:43:18,220
(GROANS)

661
00:43:37,540 --> 00:43:38,980
What? Whoa!

662
00:44:17,540 --> 00:44:19,740
(SNORING)

663
00:44:23,500 --> 00:44:25,260
(RATS CHATTERING)

664
00:44:32,900 --> 00:44:35,740
Hello? Hello?

665
00:44:36,900 --> 00:44:37,860
(GRUMBLES)

666
00:44:38,340 --> 00:44:39,300
Whoa!

667
00:44:41,860 --> 00:44:42,900
(WHISTLES)

668
00:44:42,980 --> 00:44:44,260
Lads, let's go, on the double!

669
00:44:44,380 --> 00:44:45,340
(EXCLAIMS)

670
00:44:47,940 --> 00:44:48,940
Who is that?

671
00:44:49,500 --> 00:44:50,780
Who goes there?

672
00:44:51,620 --> 00:44:52,860
Who is that?

673
00:44:52,900 --> 00:44:54,380
Despereaux Tilling.

674
00:44:54,500 --> 00:44:56,580
Are you a man or are you a mouse?

675
00:44:58,380 --> 00:45:00,900
I am a gentleman.

676
00:45:01,260 --> 00:45:02,660
(CHUCKLING) Oh.

677
00:45:03,100 --> 00:45:04,100
(RATS CLAMORING)

678
00:45:04,220 --> 00:45:05,700
- It's a mouse.
- I'm hungry.

679
00:45:05,820 --> 00:45:08,700
Shh! Quiet, lads. Patience.

680
00:45:10,020 --> 00:45:12,420
And what makes you a gentleman?

681
00:45:12,900 --> 00:45:14,140
A code...

682
00:45:14,180 --> 00:45:15,420
A code of honor.

683
00:45:15,500 --> 00:45:16,500
(LAUGHS)

684
00:45:16,580 --> 00:45:18,620
You're a strange little mouse, aren't you?

685
00:45:18,700 --> 00:45:21,060
And where did you find this code of honor?

686
00:45:21,180 --> 00:45:23,020
Well, in a legend.

687
00:45:23,140 --> 00:45:24,460
A legend that I read.

688
00:45:24,580 --> 00:45:27,180
Fine. Oh, tell me this legend of yours.

689
00:45:27,300 --> 00:45:29,420
I could do with a good story right now.

690
00:45:29,700 --> 00:45:30,980
Well,

691
00:45:31,100 --> 00:45:33,380
it's about a princess and a knight

692
00:45:34,500 --> 00:45:36,420
and his quest to save her honor.

693
00:45:36,900 --> 00:45:40,060
Ah. It was a princess
that took away my soup.

694
00:45:40,580 --> 00:45:41,980
She didn't take it.

695
00:45:42,060 --> 00:45:44,100
In fact, she misses it, too!

696
00:45:44,220 --> 00:45:45,260
(RATS MURMURING)

697
00:45:45,380 --> 00:45:47,420
How do you know all this, then?

698
00:45:47,460 --> 00:45:48,540
I've seen her.

699
00:45:48,860 --> 00:45:50,500
- Seen her?
- I've talked to her.

700
00:45:50,620 --> 00:45:52,940
- Talked to her?
- That's why they sent me down here.

701
00:45:53,060 --> 00:45:55,260
Mmm-hmm.
And what did this princess tell you

702
00:45:55,300 --> 00:45:56,900
when you had your little audience?

703
00:45:57,020 --> 00:45:58,340
(LAUGHING) Eh? Eh?

704
00:45:58,460 --> 00:46:01,100
Oh, you must be a royal mouse. Is that it?

705
00:46:01,540 --> 00:46:04,940
She told me that
she missed the soup and the rain

706
00:46:05,660 --> 00:46:07,460
and, most of all, the sunlight.

707
00:46:08,140 --> 00:46:10,620
And that she just
wanted it all to come back again.

708
00:46:13,900 --> 00:46:15,420
Well, I don't want to hear your little stories

709
00:46:15,500 --> 00:46:17,340
about princesses and sunshine.

710
00:46:18,300 --> 00:46:20,060
Go tell them to the rats!

711
00:46:20,260 --> 00:46:21,220
(GRUNTS)

712
00:46:21,700 --> 00:46:23,100
(RATS MURMURING)

713
00:46:26,460 --> 00:46:27,660
All right, boys, come on!

714
00:46:27,780 --> 00:46:29,260
(RATS SHOUTING)

715
00:46:41,220 --> 00:46:42,500
(CROWD CHEERING)

716
00:46:53,740 --> 00:46:54,740
(GRUNTING)

717
00:47:04,260 --> 00:47:05,260
(LAUGHING)

718
00:47:06,540 --> 00:47:07,780
Good crowd, isn't it, sir?

719
00:47:08,380 --> 00:47:10,300
Yes, it is, quite.

720
00:47:10,380 --> 00:47:12,420
CROWD: (CHANTING) Mouse! Mouse!
Mouse! Mouse!

721
00:47:19,140 --> 00:47:22,300
Ah, Roscuro! I'm glad you could make it.

722
00:47:22,380 --> 00:47:24,780
I thought you didn't like the arena.

723
00:47:24,900 --> 00:47:27,900
Huh? Oh! No, no. It... It's an honor, sir.

724
00:47:28,540 --> 00:47:29,540
Oh!

725
00:47:29,660 --> 00:47:30,780
- BOTTICELLl: Good.
- Mmm.

726
00:47:30,980 --> 00:47:32,900
Well, enjoy.

727
00:47:33,340 --> 00:47:36,220
(STAMMERING) Oh, uh... Thank you.

728
00:47:36,300 --> 00:47:38,020
(CROWD CHEERING)

729
00:47:41,060 --> 00:47:42,940
Let the games begin!

730
00:47:51,140 --> 00:47:52,100
(ANIMAL SQUEALING)

731
00:47:55,740 --> 00:47:58,300
CROWD: (CHANTING) Mouse! Mouse! Mouse!

732
00:48:03,780 --> 00:48:05,100
(MEOWING)

733
00:48:05,260 --> 00:48:06,620
(CROWD CHEERING)

734
00:48:14,980 --> 00:48:16,220
(CROWD GROANING)

735
00:48:16,260 --> 00:48:17,260
RAT: Come on!

736
00:48:21,100 --> 00:48:22,340
(SNARLS)

737
00:48:22,500 --> 00:48:23,460
(MEOWS)

738
00:48:26,180 --> 00:48:27,700
(CROWD CHEERING)

739
00:48:30,460 --> 00:48:31,420
(SQUEALS)

740
00:48:57,260 --> 00:48:58,260
(SNARLS)

741
00:48:58,980 --> 00:48:59,980
Hold on!

742
00:49:06,060 --> 00:49:08,300
CROWD: (CHANTING) Eat! Eat! Eat!

743
00:49:13,380 --> 00:49:14,940
(RAT SHOUTING)

744
00:49:17,860 --> 00:49:18,820
ROSCURO: Wait!

745
00:49:19,140 --> 00:49:22,780
(STAMMERING) Can I have him?
Can I have this one? Please?

746
00:49:23,140 --> 00:49:25,020
(CROWD GRUMBLING)

747
00:49:26,300 --> 00:49:27,260
What?

748
00:49:27,660 --> 00:49:30,820
It's just that that one looks tasty.

749
00:49:30,980 --> 00:49:33,500
Well, this is progress.

750
00:49:33,580 --> 00:49:37,580
Perhaps we're starting
to leave the past behind us, eh?

751
00:49:37,700 --> 00:49:39,980
Enjoy, my friend.

752
00:49:40,100 --> 00:49:42,220
Don't leave a morsel.

753
00:49:42,340 --> 00:49:44,540
(STAMMERING) Oh, I won't.

754
00:49:45,380 --> 00:49:46,380
(SNAPS)

755
00:49:46,500 --> 00:49:47,460
Pull!

756
00:49:49,060 --> 00:49:50,060
(WHIMPERS)

757
00:49:50,220 --> 00:49:51,940
(CROWD GRUMBLING)

758
00:49:54,660 --> 00:49:56,380
(ALL CLAMORING)

759
00:50:03,140 --> 00:50:05,500
Come on, let's go, buster!

760
00:50:05,860 --> 00:50:08,700
That's it. That's it. You keep moving!

761
00:50:10,700 --> 00:50:13,420
(WHISPERING) It's okay. Keep walking.

762
00:50:13,700 --> 00:50:17,060
Come on, keep moving! Let's go, come on!

763
00:50:18,980 --> 00:50:20,380
(WHISPERING) It's right up there.

764
00:50:28,100 --> 00:50:29,660
- Huh?
- Keep walking.

765
00:50:37,020 --> 00:50:38,300
- Oh.
- See that?

766
00:50:39,340 --> 00:50:41,100
Light. Real light.

767
00:50:42,540 --> 00:50:44,900
It's mine, but you can share it.

768
00:50:45,540 --> 00:50:49,380
It isn't much, but there isn't much anywhere
since everything turned gray.

769
00:50:51,340 --> 00:50:52,900
You're not gonna eat me?

770
00:50:53,380 --> 00:50:55,460
No. I don't eat mice.

771
00:50:55,780 --> 00:50:57,180
Then what do you eat?

772
00:50:57,380 --> 00:50:58,460
Crumbs.

773
00:50:58,540 --> 00:50:59,820
When I can find them.

774
00:51:01,260 --> 00:51:03,500
So you are a gentleman.

775
00:51:06,180 --> 00:51:07,660
Tell me that story.

776
00:51:08,580 --> 00:51:09,980
About the Princess.

777
00:51:10,780 --> 00:51:12,540
Tell me what she looked like.

778
00:51:13,100 --> 00:51:14,820
Well, she was...

779
00:51:14,940 --> 00:51:16,140
Was she angry?

780
00:51:16,260 --> 00:51:17,380
No.

781
00:51:17,500 --> 00:51:19,100
No, not at all.

782
00:51:19,140 --> 00:51:21,980
Her heart was full of longing.

783
00:51:23,500 --> 00:51:25,020
What's longing?

784
00:51:26,860 --> 00:51:29,660
<i>NARRATOR: And that's
how a friendship is born.</i>

785
00:51:30,340 --> 00:51:34,180
<i>Over the next few weeks, he told Roscuro
everything he knew about loyalty</i>

786
00:51:34,300 --> 00:51:36,540
<i>and honor and chivalry and courage.</i>

787
00:51:36,580 --> 00:51:39,780
<i>He told him about the Princess,
and where her longing came from.</i>

788
00:51:39,900 --> 00:51:43,580
<i>That she missed the rain and the soup
and even the rats.</i>

789
00:51:44,820 --> 00:51:45,860
Even the rats?

790
00:51:46,580 --> 00:51:50,580
<i>NARRATOR: He told him about their
code of honor, about his noble quest,</i>

791
00:51:50,980 --> 00:51:53,180
<i>about duty and loyalty.</i>

792
00:51:53,700 --> 00:51:56,660
<i>And there, in the darkness of the cellar,</i>

793
00:51:56,740 --> 00:52:01,660
<i>two knights pledged devotion to a princess
who was trapped inside a castle.</i>

794
00:52:02,940 --> 00:52:05,340
<i>Trapped in a life full of pain and longing.</i>

795
00:52:05,460 --> 00:52:07,260
<i>Even if no one could tell.</i>

796
00:52:11,260 --> 00:52:13,020
Your crown, ma'am.

797
00:52:14,180 --> 00:52:15,220
Oh.

798
00:52:16,220 --> 00:52:17,780
I don't want it today.

799
00:52:17,860 --> 00:52:19,580
But it's beautiful, ma'am.

800
00:52:19,900 --> 00:52:21,980
I know, but I don't want it.

801
00:52:22,020 --> 00:52:24,540
You look so pretty in it, ma'am.

802
00:52:24,580 --> 00:52:26,420
Like a princess.

803
00:52:26,660 --> 00:52:29,540
I know. I am the princess.

804
00:52:29,780 --> 00:52:31,260
Oh, I know, ma'am,

805
00:52:31,380 --> 00:52:35,420
but such a fine princess,
with a little, pretty, glittery...

806
00:52:35,460 --> 00:52:37,020
I don't want it!

807
00:52:37,140 --> 00:52:38,460
All right, Mig?

808
00:52:39,460 --> 00:52:41,020
Very well, ma'am.

809
00:52:41,620 --> 00:52:43,260
Please, take it away.

810
00:52:59,620 --> 00:53:00,580
MIG: Princess.

811
00:53:01,700 --> 00:53:03,100
Who's the princess?

812
00:53:03,740 --> 00:53:05,300
I'm a princess.

813
00:53:05,380 --> 00:53:07,220
I'm the princess.

814
00:53:08,980 --> 00:53:13,620
My comb, my hat, my gloves

815
00:53:14,620 --> 00:53:18,420
and my pretty powder

816
00:53:18,500 --> 00:53:20,980
on my pretty princess face.

817
00:53:21,140 --> 00:53:23,220
And what do you think you're doing?

818
00:53:23,300 --> 00:53:24,260
Ma'am!

819
00:53:24,380 --> 00:53:26,820
Where did you get all this?

820
00:53:26,940 --> 00:53:28,700
I just borrowed it, ma'am.

821
00:53:28,740 --> 00:53:29,820
Borrowed it?

822
00:53:30,140 --> 00:53:32,100
I was gonna put them all back.

823
00:53:32,260 --> 00:53:33,500
See that you do!

824
00:53:34,940 --> 00:53:37,660
And you can spend the whole week

825
00:53:37,780 --> 00:53:39,540
taking slop to the dungeon

826
00:53:39,620 --> 00:53:41,620
for your little escapade.

827
00:53:42,500 --> 00:53:43,740
"Princess"!

828
00:53:47,260 --> 00:53:50,020
God! She's the princess.

829
00:53:50,140 --> 00:53:51,140
(SCOFFS)

830
00:53:51,260 --> 00:53:55,700
And now I have to carry the sloppy,
gloppy, stinky stew

831
00:53:55,780 --> 00:53:58,340
down in the damp, dark, dingy...

832
00:54:00,500 --> 00:54:02,740
A person could get lost forever down here.

833
00:54:04,740 --> 00:54:05,780
Oh!

834
00:54:05,860 --> 00:54:06,900
(SNORING)

835
00:54:07,420 --> 00:54:08,380
Din-din.

836
00:54:09,860 --> 00:54:10,820
Slop.

837
00:54:13,140 --> 00:54:16,660
No, don't stop! I said "slop"!

838
00:54:20,260 --> 00:54:21,300
(SIGHS)

839
00:54:21,380 --> 00:54:23,700
How am I supposed to eat this swill?

840
00:54:24,700 --> 00:54:27,900
Oh, stop that!
I don't have to be putting up with all this!

841
00:54:29,340 --> 00:54:30,940
I serve the Princess.

842
00:54:31,580 --> 00:54:32,900
(LAUGHING)

843
00:54:33,060 --> 00:54:35,580
Right. You serve the Princess.

844
00:54:35,700 --> 00:54:38,460
- That's a bit of a laugh, isn't it?
- I do.

845
00:54:38,580 --> 00:54:41,180
- I bring her tea and...
- Well, I don't want to hear it!

846
00:54:42,020 --> 00:54:43,900
Had me own little princess once.

847
00:54:44,420 --> 00:54:45,620
And now I don't.

848
00:54:46,020 --> 00:54:48,540
Oh. What, you had a princess?

849
00:54:50,340 --> 00:54:51,380
Yeah.

850
00:54:51,460 --> 00:54:53,660
Every dad's got a princess.

851
00:54:54,340 --> 00:54:56,340
<i>GREGORY: Till he stops being a dad,
of course.</i>

852
00:54:56,420 --> 00:54:57,660
(BABY COOING)

853
00:54:59,220 --> 00:55:01,940
Sorry. So, so, sorry!

854
00:55:03,580 --> 00:55:05,380
Oh, well, I've got a real one.

855
00:55:05,500 --> 00:55:08,420
And she's got a tiara and fancy robes,

856
00:55:08,540 --> 00:55:11,140
and she's got shiny bits
all over every frock in her closet.

857
00:55:11,260 --> 00:55:13,980
And I get to see her every single day.

858
00:55:15,060 --> 00:55:16,540
DESPEREAUX: What kind of a quest?

859
00:55:16,660 --> 00:55:17,620
Uh...

860
00:55:18,420 --> 00:55:20,100
To right a terrible wrong.

861
00:55:20,540 --> 00:55:22,460
But who did you wrong?

862
00:55:25,220 --> 00:55:26,180
Okay.

863
00:55:27,700 --> 00:55:30,300
Do you remember when
they banished the rats?

864
00:55:30,820 --> 00:55:32,380
- Sure. Yes.
- Okay.

865
00:55:33,180 --> 00:55:35,100
Well, it wasn't all the rats they banished.

866
00:55:35,140 --> 00:55:39,420
I mean, they did,
but it was all because of one particular rat

867
00:55:40,220 --> 00:55:41,660
in particular.

868
00:55:41,820 --> 00:55:42,780
Oh.

869
00:55:44,020 --> 00:55:44,980
Mmm-hmm.

870
00:55:45,060 --> 00:55:46,740
If I could just tell her I'm sorry,

871
00:55:46,820 --> 00:55:50,940
that I'm, you know, I'm really sorry.

872
00:55:51,060 --> 00:55:53,660
And that I didn't mean
for any of this to happen.

873
00:55:53,700 --> 00:55:55,580
If she could just hear me say it,

874
00:55:55,620 --> 00:55:57,980
you know, just... Just hear my voice,

875
00:55:58,100 --> 00:56:01,180
(STAMMERING) she would
know how much I meant it.

876
00:56:02,940 --> 00:56:04,700
That is a very noble quest.

877
00:56:19,460 --> 00:56:21,780
ROSCURO: (STAMMERING) Your Highness?

878
00:56:24,580 --> 00:56:26,420
Your Highness?

879
00:56:27,460 --> 00:56:28,860
Is that you?

880
00:56:29,140 --> 00:56:30,460
My little mouse?

881
00:56:31,100 --> 00:56:32,900
Oh, I'm not a mouse. I...

882
00:56:33,380 --> 00:56:34,740
(STAMMERING) I'm a...

883
00:56:36,180 --> 00:56:37,140
Oh.

884
00:56:37,660 --> 00:56:38,740
I forgot.

885
00:56:38,980 --> 00:56:41,180
You're my little gentleman, aren't you?

886
00:56:44,100 --> 00:56:46,020
Have you come to tell me
how the story ends?

887
00:56:46,140 --> 00:56:47,740
Did you finish your quest?

888
00:56:48,900 --> 00:56:50,300
Where are you?

889
00:56:51,460 --> 00:56:53,340
I have come to apologize.

890
00:56:53,940 --> 00:56:56,340
Oh, you are noble, remember?

891
00:56:57,180 --> 00:56:59,260
You have nothing to be sorry about.

892
00:57:00,820 --> 00:57:02,180
Oh, but I am.

893
00:57:05,140 --> 00:57:06,500
I am sorry.

894
00:57:09,380 --> 00:57:11,220
(GASPING) I know you.

895
00:57:11,300 --> 00:57:13,660
- No, no.
- Oh, no!

896
00:57:13,780 --> 00:57:15,460
No! Please, please listen. Please.

897
00:57:15,580 --> 00:57:16,860
- A rat!
- Please. I just want to tell you.

898
00:57:16,980 --> 00:57:18,500
(SCREAMING) Someone, please!

899
00:57:18,620 --> 00:57:19,740
Listen. It's okay.

900
00:57:19,860 --> 00:57:22,140
Get it off me! There's a rat in my room!

901
00:57:22,460 --> 00:57:24,180
Please get him off!

902
00:57:24,260 --> 00:57:26,420
(SCREAMING)

903
00:57:29,700 --> 00:57:30,660
What?

904
00:57:32,220 --> 00:57:33,220
(PRINCESS PEA SHRIEKING)

905
00:57:36,260 --> 00:57:37,300
Rat!

906
00:57:37,820 --> 00:57:39,540
(PRINCESS PEA SHRIEKING)

907
00:57:39,620 --> 00:57:40,660
Oh!

908
00:57:41,940 --> 00:57:43,860
PRINCESS PEA: It's a rat!

909
00:57:50,620 --> 00:57:52,100
GUARD 1: Quick, rush him!

910
00:57:52,220 --> 00:57:53,220
GUARD 2: Get him!

911
00:57:53,340 --> 00:57:54,620
GUARD 3: Filthy rodent!

912
00:58:00,900 --> 00:58:01,940
Uh-oh.

913
00:58:03,260 --> 00:58:04,220
Oh!

914
00:58:09,220 --> 00:58:10,740
GUARD: Where'd he go?

915
00:58:18,460 --> 00:58:19,460
(GRUNTING)

916
00:58:21,340 --> 00:58:22,740
(PANTING)

917
00:58:49,980 --> 00:58:53,500
<i>NARRATOR: What would you do
if your own name was a bad word?</i>

918
00:58:55,580 --> 00:58:59,020
<i>If John or Beth or Bill was an insult.</i>

919
00:59:00,500 --> 00:59:03,820
<i>Well, that's how Roscuro
came to feel about who he was.</i>

920
00:59:05,820 --> 00:59:09,620
<i>When your heart breaks,
it can grow back crooked.</i>

921
00:59:10,620 --> 00:59:14,220
<i>It grows back twisted and gnarled and hard.</i>

922
00:59:16,460 --> 00:59:19,700
<i>Even as he changed,
Roscuro still had longing.</i>

923
00:59:20,700 --> 00:59:24,860
<i>But now he just longed for someone whose
heart was as hardened as his was.</i>

924
00:59:25,860 --> 00:59:31,180
Pretty princess. Pretty, pretty princess pie.

925
00:59:32,220 --> 00:59:34,140
What a pretty princess!

926
00:59:35,740 --> 00:59:37,020
My gloves.

927
00:59:37,820 --> 00:59:39,020
My comb.

928
00:59:40,260 --> 00:59:42,860
My jewel-y, girly hat,

929
00:59:43,260 --> 00:59:47,420
all sitting on my princess head.

930
00:59:50,620 --> 00:59:55,740
Who's the pretty princess pumpkin pie?

931
00:59:58,620 --> 00:59:59,580
You are.

932
00:59:59,900 --> 01:00:02,420
Right. I am.

933
01:00:02,700 --> 01:00:06,300
You are. And you should be
dressed in those clothes.

934
01:00:06,940 --> 01:00:09,660
Quite right. I should.

935
01:00:09,820 --> 01:00:12,700
Mmm-hmm.
And you should lounge in that bed.

936
01:00:12,780 --> 01:00:13,980
Lounging.

937
01:00:14,100 --> 01:00:17,820
Lounging round, yes, the whole day!

938
01:00:18,220 --> 01:00:20,620
And you should be wearing that crown.

939
01:00:21,420 --> 01:00:22,940
I should be wearing a frown?

940
01:00:23,060 --> 01:00:26,620
No. No, no, no. Not a frown. A crown.

941
01:00:26,700 --> 01:00:29,780
Wow! Can't hear me own self think.

942
01:00:32,340 --> 01:00:33,500
- Ah!
- Shh!

943
01:00:33,620 --> 01:00:35,540
- Ah!
- Shh!

944
01:00:36,180 --> 01:00:37,180
Shh!

945
01:00:37,300 --> 01:00:38,940
- Ah!
- Shh!

946
01:00:40,660 --> 01:00:42,060
Who are you?

947
01:00:42,140 --> 01:00:43,660
I'm here to help you.

948
01:00:43,740 --> 01:00:46,220
I can't be caught with a real rat in my bunk.

949
01:00:46,700 --> 01:00:48,300
I don't think so.

950
01:00:48,380 --> 01:00:49,340
(INHALES)

951
01:00:50,300 --> 01:00:52,780
And what if they find you
with a painting of the Princess?

952
01:00:52,860 --> 01:00:54,740
You think that's as bad as a rat?

953
01:00:55,500 --> 01:00:57,100
I want the same thing you do.

954
01:01:06,140 --> 01:01:07,540
(CLANKING)

955
01:01:08,540 --> 01:01:09,500
<i>Allo?</i>

956
01:01:11,860 --> 01:01:14,420
(BOTH EXCLAIMING)

957
01:01:14,500 --> 01:01:15,500
What are you doing?

958
01:01:15,740 --> 01:01:16,700
Uh...

959
01:01:17,620 --> 01:01:19,420
I need it for a baby.

960
01:01:21,260 --> 01:01:23,020
No, not a baby!

961
01:01:23,500 --> 01:01:24,500
For milady.

962
01:01:24,620 --> 01:01:27,260
(STAMMERING) I mean milady.

963
01:01:27,940 --> 01:01:28,980
Yes.

964
01:01:29,460 --> 01:01:30,620
To chop apples.

965
01:01:30,740 --> 01:01:31,700
Mmm.

966
01:01:31,820 --> 01:01:33,180
She'd like some apples.

967
01:01:35,740 --> 01:01:36,860
Now turn and leave.

968
01:01:36,940 --> 01:01:38,780
Now turn and leave.

969
01:01:41,180 --> 01:01:44,180
No, no! Just turn and leave.

970
01:01:44,380 --> 01:01:46,060
Oh, right. Sorry.

971
01:01:46,620 --> 01:01:47,580
Sorry. Bye.

972
01:01:47,700 --> 01:01:50,860
Oh, I can't hear you, see, because deaf, but...

973
01:01:50,980 --> 01:01:51,980
A bit deaf.

974
01:01:55,020 --> 01:01:57,460
<i>NARRATOR: You know, hurt is a funny thing.</i>

975
01:01:57,500 --> 01:02:01,940
<i>The same thing that makes one person angry
can put another person into grief.</i>

976
01:02:01,980 --> 01:02:04,620
Here, take care of me little princess.

977
01:02:04,860 --> 01:02:06,420
I can't no more.

978
01:02:06,620 --> 01:02:09,100
Oh, I will. Don't worry.

979
01:02:09,980 --> 01:02:11,020
(BABY COOING)

980
01:02:11,100 --> 01:02:12,140
I'm sorry.

981
01:02:12,820 --> 01:02:15,700
Sorry. So, so sorry!

982
01:02:18,740 --> 01:02:21,740
<i>NARRATOR: Gregory always said
that she had too much heart.</i>

983
01:02:21,820 --> 01:02:25,420
<i>And that's why they had to put
some of it on the outside.</i>

984
01:02:25,500 --> 01:02:26,860
<i>But let's face it.</i>

985
01:02:26,940 --> 01:02:29,500
<i>It's hard to see something on your back.</i>

986
01:02:29,580 --> 01:02:33,500
<i>In fact, you can have a good heart
and not even know it.</i>

987
01:02:33,660 --> 01:02:35,340
You can do this. You know you can.

988
01:02:35,740 --> 01:02:36,940
I know I can.

989
01:02:37,020 --> 01:02:41,460
She belongs in the dungeon,
and you belong in the palace, like a princess.

990
01:02:42,940 --> 01:02:44,060
(CLATTERING)

991
01:02:46,900 --> 01:02:48,020
What are you doing?

992
01:02:49,260 --> 01:02:50,380
I'm cleaning, ma'am.

993
01:02:50,460 --> 01:02:51,420
(GROANS)

994
01:02:51,820 --> 01:02:53,100
With rope?

995
01:02:53,260 --> 01:02:54,260
It helps, ma'am.

996
01:02:54,300 --> 01:02:56,140
Well, stop it. You look ridiculous.

997
01:02:58,620 --> 01:02:59,700
Sorry, ma'am?

998
01:02:59,820 --> 01:03:02,260
I said you look ridiculous.

999
01:03:02,380 --> 01:03:05,500
<i>(ECHOING) Ridiculous,
ridiculous, ridiculous.</i>

1000
01:03:07,340 --> 01:03:08,940
- You can't do this, Mig.
- Gor.

1001
01:03:09,180 --> 01:03:10,740
Seems I am, ma'am.

1002
01:03:10,820 --> 01:03:12,220
You'll get in a terrible amount of trouble.

1003
01:03:12,300 --> 01:03:14,220
Don't listen. You're the princess now.

1004
01:03:14,300 --> 01:03:15,700
I'm the princess now.

1005
01:03:15,820 --> 01:03:17,460
And you belong in the palace.

1006
01:03:17,540 --> 01:03:19,100
I belong in the palace.

1007
01:03:19,180 --> 01:03:20,180
And she belongs in...

1008
01:03:20,300 --> 01:03:22,220
PRINCESS PEA: No! You can't do this!

1009
01:03:22,300 --> 01:03:25,420
Help! Help! Someone help me!

1010
01:03:25,500 --> 01:03:27,380
Help! Help!

1011
01:03:28,140 --> 01:03:30,580
(FAINTLY) Help! Help!

1012
01:03:36,020 --> 01:03:37,980
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

1013
01:03:39,260 --> 01:03:41,020
PRINCESS PEA: Help! Help!

1014
01:03:42,900 --> 01:03:44,300
Help!

1015
01:03:45,180 --> 01:03:46,940
MIG: I'm in here!

1016
01:03:48,820 --> 01:03:50,260
Help!

1017
01:03:50,580 --> 01:03:52,380
You filthy, stinking rat!

1018
01:03:53,460 --> 01:03:54,860
You tricked me!

1019
01:03:55,100 --> 01:03:56,940
(RATS CLAMORING)

1020
01:03:57,660 --> 01:03:58,740
RAT 1: Here's the spot, rats!

1021
01:03:58,820 --> 01:04:00,140
SMUDGE: What's Roscuro brought us, then?

1022
01:04:00,220 --> 01:04:01,580
RAT 2: Hungry! Yum! Hungry now!

1023
01:04:01,660 --> 01:04:03,420
Not yet, lads. No, no, you've got to wait.

1024
01:04:03,500 --> 01:04:04,860
It's nowhere near dinnertime.

1025
01:04:04,940 --> 01:04:06,900
Oh, come on, Smudge, I'm starving.

1026
01:04:06,940 --> 01:04:08,540
(PRINCESS PEA SOBBING)

1027
01:04:12,060 --> 01:04:14,300
RAT 1: Something special for dinner tonight.

1028
01:04:14,620 --> 01:04:16,060
RAT 3: Smells delicious!

1029
01:04:18,100 --> 01:04:21,100
RAT 2: Smells human to me. A young one.
RAT 3: And not just any human.

1030
01:04:21,180 --> 01:04:23,100
RAT 2: Let's have a look.
RAT 3: It's the Princess!

1031
01:04:23,220 --> 01:04:24,980
SMUDGE: Oi, you'll wait
for your dinner like everyone else.

1032
01:04:25,020 --> 01:04:26,060
RAT 2: Come on, Smudge,
give us a little look.

1033
01:04:26,140 --> 01:04:27,180
SMUDGE: No, no, no!

1034
01:04:27,260 --> 01:04:29,620
SMUDGE: Boss doesn't want her
getting nervous. Spoils the meat, doesn't it?

1035
01:04:32,220 --> 01:04:33,260
(CRYING)

1036
01:04:34,140 --> 01:04:35,540
DESPEREAUX: Milady!

1037
01:04:35,900 --> 01:04:37,740
Psst! Milady!

1038
01:04:38,380 --> 01:04:41,300
Oh, my little mouse! It's you.

1039
01:04:41,500 --> 01:04:43,740
I will deliver you from this evil, ma'am.

